Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: An 'Affiliate' or Not? For Investor Cash, It Matters
Headlines.Author: James Willhite
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: An 'Affiliate' or Not? For Investor Cash, It Matters

PARAGRAPH.#text: Is your in-house consulting unit an "affiliate," or a "variable-interest entity?" Private-equity firm KKR & Co. is learning that it's critical to apply specific language to such matters across all of its regulatory filings, because the distinction has a big impact on whether the fees that the unit collects need to be shared with investors.

Headlines.Author: Laura Mandaro
Headlines.Headline: MARKET SNAPSHOT: Here's What Could Wake Up Stocks This Week

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Laura Mandaro, MarketWatch Will the next catalyst for the stock market please step forward? After U.S. stocks' best January in 15 months, stocks spent the first full week of February in a tight zigzag around five-year highs. Investors sat on the sidelines, they treaded water, they lacked conviction -- in other words, they used up a lot of Wall Street's favorite clichés for not doing much at all. Volume was low, capped by the lowest volume day of the year Friday as many on Wall Street headed out early ahead of a commute-clogging winter storm.

Headlines.Author: Melodie Warner
Headlines.Headline: Lorillard 3rd-Quarter Net Rises 6% on Improved Margins, Higher Revenue

PARAGRAPH.#text: Lorillard Inc.'s LO third-quarter earnings rose 6%, as better-than-expected revenue growth contributed to improved margins. "Lorillard once again strengthened its position in the U.S. cigarette market during the third quarter, as it grew market share, sales, margins and average net pricing, all of which translated to strong EPS growth over last year," said Chairman and Chief Executive Murray S. Kessler. The No. 3 U.S. cigarette producer by revenue dominates the market for menthol cigarettes, which are increasingly popular among younger smokers, though overall smoking rates have declined, pressuring its bottom line.

Headlines.Author: Nathalie Tadena
Headlines.Headline: Lorillard Authorizes $500 Million in Share Buybacks

PARAGRAPH.#text: Lorillard Inc. LO authorized up to $500 million in share repurchases, as the tobacco company looks to boost shareholder value. The No. 3 U.S. cigarette producer by revenue dominates the market for menthol cigarettes, said the repurchase program has no set expiration date and said the program will be funded with existing cash balances. The company had $946 million in cash and cash equivalents as of June 30. Lorillard completed a $750 million share repurchase plan earlier this year, but didn't buy back shares in the second quarter.

PARAGRAPH.#text: --CEO says Reynolds American notched higher earnings despite ongoing intense promotional environment and weak economy --Domestic cigarette shipment volume slid 6.7%, worse than the industry's decline and underperforming Altria --American Snuff volume jumped 11%, more than double the industry's growth rate (Updates with details from the company's conference call, Altria results, additional background and the latest stock quote) Reynolds American Inc.'s RAI second-quarter earnings rose 35% due to higher prices for cigarettes and stronger volume and pricing for moist snuff, helping to offset the tobacco company's cigarette sales decline.

Headlines.Author: Wallace Witkowski
Headlines.Headline: U.S. stock gains hinge on Apple, blue-chip results

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Lorillard Inc.'s LO second-quarter earnings rose 11% as the cigarette maker's sales benefited from increased volume and higher selling prices. The No. 3 U.S. cigarette producer by revenue dominates the market for menthol cigarettes, which are increasingly popular with adolescents and young adults, though overall smoking rates have declined. Bigger rivals Altria Group Inc. (MO) and Reynolds American Inc. (RAI) last week both reported weaker quarterly results amid charges. Altria and Reynolds have been relying more on the popularity of smokeless-tobacco products as cigarette volume continues to decline.

Headlines.Author: Dave Kansas
Headlines.Headline: Stocks to Watch: Coach, Delta, Hershey and More

PARAGRAPH.#text: Some stocks to watch this morning, courtesy of our friends at Dow Jones.Verizon Wireless and USA Technologies Inc. said they will collaborate to deliver cashless payment services and machine-to-machine applications via USA Technologies' ePort Connect Service. Shares of USA Technologies jumped 16% premarket to $3.34.Delta Air Lines says higher ticket prices will help it fully recover fuel costs in the second half, a more bullish outlook than US network peers relying also on ancillary revenue. Unit passenger revenue seen up by double-digits in 2Q after a rise of 7% in the three months to March 31. Delta was weighed down by more rapid expansion on transatlantic routes in the first quarter-- the only region to see a decline in unit revenue -- but is trimming weaker services across its network. Capacity after Labor Day will be trimmed by 3%. Shares up 2.1% at $9.19 premarket.Coach Inc.'s fiscal third-quarter earnings rose 18%, beating analysts' estimates, as the luxury-accessories maker also raised its quarterly dividend by 50%.Cooper Tire & Rubber Co.'s first-quarter profit surged 35%, beating Wall Street's estimates, as sales soared in its North American and international units, though higher raw material costs weighed on the company.Hershey Co.'s first-quarter profit rose 8.6% and core results topped analysts' expectations as it reaped the results of U.S. and international brand growth, new products and a seasonal shift in volume.IAC/InterActive Corp. swung to a first-quarter profit as the Web-properties company saw revenue climb by more than one-fifth.Lorillard Inc.'s first-quarter earnings grew 6.9% on higher unit volume and higher prices, though the cigarette-maker also reported higher sales promotion costs as it pushes its new Newport Non-Menthol line.Waddell & Reed Financial Inc.'s first-quarter profit jumped 27% as higher fees drove an increase in revenue, though results fell just short of  all Street's expectations.

Headlines.Author: Jennifer Corbett
Headlines.Headline: Lorillard, RJ Reynolds Sue FDA Over Menthol Review Panel

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Updates with FDA, Reynolds comments.) WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--Two major tobacco firms filed a lawsuit against the Food and Drug Administration Friday over the agency's review of menthol cigarettes, claiming some members of an FDA panel have conflicts of interest. Specifically, Lorillard, Inc. LO and R.J. Reynolds, part of Reynolds American Inc. RAI, have sued to stop the agency from receiving or relying on recommendations from its tobacco products advisory committee. The suit alleges that the Tobacco Products Scientific Advisory Committee as currently constituted fails to meet requirements of the Federal Advisory Committee Act to be fairly balanced and not to be inappropriately influenced by any special interest.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Lorillard, RJ Reynolds Sue FDA Over Menthol Review Panel

The suit alleges that the Tobacco Products Scientific Advisory Committee as currently constituted fails to meet requirements of the Federal Advisory Committee Act to be fairly balanced and not to be inappropriately influenced by any special interest.

The agency said products such as cigarettes, roll-your-own tobacco and smokeless products that were introduced or changed after Feb. 15, 2007 must be reviewed by the agency to show that they are "substantially equivalent" to products commercially available on Feb. 15, 2007. Headlines.Headline: BEFORE THE BELL:US Stock Futures Drop Further On Economic Concerns

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Simon Kennedy U.S. stock market futures pointed to a further decline on Wall Street Friday as investors remained wary after the previous session's disappointing data. Dow Industrial futures fell 50 points to 10,185 and S&P 500 futures dropped 5.80 points to 1,065.50. Futures on the Nasdaq 100 were down 7.75 points at 1,812.25. U.S. markets fell sharply Thursday after weak data on the jobs market and regional manufacturing reignited fears about the economic recovery. The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed down over 144 points, with all 30 components ending the day in the red.

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Lorillard Inc.

chose tobacco-industry veteran Murray S. Kessler as its new president and chief executive, succeeding Martin L. Orlowsky. Orlowsky, who has served as CEO since 1999, also announced he plans to retire as chairman effective Dec. 31 when his employment contract expires. He plans to stay on in an advisory role for two years thereafter. Lorillard's board began looking for a successor in November.

Headlines.Author: Recent Setbacks
Headlines.Headline: Cigarette Cos Burned By Recent Setbacks In Tiny Tobacco Suits

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Thousands of small lawsuits, remnants of a failed class action case, are turning into a lingering headache for the U.S. tobacco industry. The so-called Engle progeny cases in Florida--individual lawsuits that sprang up after court rulings broke up a class action by the same name--have been arriving for trial in recent months, with plaintiffs racking up a number of recent wins against the cigarette makers. With several thousand such cases on file, navigating these long-running suits could turn into an expensive and laborious prospect for large tobacco companies like Altria Group Inc.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Cigarette Cos Burned By Recent Setbacks In Tiny Tobacco Suits

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Updates with comment from President Barack Obama and FDA Commissioner Margaret Hamburg.) WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--A bill allowing the U.S. Food and Drug Administration to regulate tobacco is on the way to the White House for President Barack Obama's signature. A day after the U.S. Senate overwhelmingly approved the measure, the House passed it Friday on a 307-97 vote. Obama said Friday that passage of the measure "truly defines change in Washington." "For over a decade, leaders of both parties have fought to prevent tobacco companies from marketing their products to children, and provide the public with the information they need to understand what a dangerous habit this is," Obama said.

Headlines.Author: Fawn Johnson
Headlines.Headline: UPDATE=Final Senate Passage In Sight For Tobacco Control Bill

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Updates with vote detail and additional background.) WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--The Senate on Wednesday cleared the last hurdle toward passage of a long-debated bill to give the Food and Drug Administration authority to regulate tobacco. A final vote is expected Thursday, according to Sen. Chris Dodd, D-Conn. The House passed a similar bill in April. President Barack Obama has expressed support for the measure and is expected to sign it once the two chambers work out their differences. The 67-30 procedural vote shows considerable bipartisan support for the legislation, which has been in the works for more than a decade.

Headlines.Headline: Lorillard Expects To Issue Debt; May Buy Back Stock

#text: Dow Jones Newswires NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Tobacco company Lorillard Inc.

expects to issue to $750 million to $1 billion of debt in the near term and will consider using those funds for share buybacks, executives said on a conference call with analysts. Lorillard is projecting long-term revenue growth of 3% to 5% and long term per share earnings growth of 5% to 7%. The company said it will be able to sustain operating margins in the 32% to 33% range.
